			<p>Beyond the bustling cities and breakneck modernization lies China&rsquo;s mysterious and ancient folk culture.<br />
<br />
Generations of artists, their work and village life are all part of a new photo exhibition at the University of Central Florida by four students involved in an international preservation effort.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Expressions of China&rdquo; opened this week in UCF&rsquo;s Burnett Honors College, with 30 selected works from the students&rsquo; travels through the rural villages of Shandong Province and the larger cities of Jinan, Beijing and Shanghai earlier this year. <br />
<br />
The exhibit is the latest extension of UCF&rsquo;s ChinaVine project, an interactive research effort aimed at teaching English-speaking audiences about longstanding Chinese customs and traditional art through modern technology. On its Web site, <a href="http://www.chinavine.org">ChinaVine.org</a>, UCF art, film and digital media students have placed photographs and video footage of Chinese folk art and village life. <br />
<br />
&ldquo;I wanted to go for the experience,&rdquo; said Blair Remington, one of the student artists who contributed to the photo exhibit. &ldquo;The experience of being welcomed into the homes of artists who are keeping centuries-old traditions alive. And the experience of feeling an indescribable connection between our cultures.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
ChinaVine is a collaboration between UCF and the University of Oregon, along with two universities in China, Shandong University of Art and Design and Beijing Normal University. <br />
<br />
During the past two years, the UCF team, made up of students and professors, has traveled to China four times.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;In these revealing photographs, the artists explore a changing and dynamic country that celebrates its past, embraces its future and is full of resilient, energized and hopeful people,&rdquo; said Kristin Congdon, a UCF film and philosophy professor leading the ChinaVine project. <br />
<br />
Unable to speak Chinese when he traveled through Shandong Province in March, another student artist and the project&rsquo;s manager, Tomas Valladares, said his camera provided a way to communicate. Showing people their pictures &ldquo;broke the ice,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;And they responded with smiles and laughter, providing us with an instant connection.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
The exhibit will be on display at UCF through Jan. 5 and then will travel to the University of Oregon. When the exhibit returns to Florida, the photos will be placed in an Orange County library or other public buildings. <br />
<br />
&ldquo;Expressions of China&rdquo; is made up of works by UCF students Remington, Valladares, Ian Hernand and Sharon Weaver. <br />
<br />
To learn more about ChinaVine, go to <a href="http://www.ChinaVine.org">www.ChinaVine.org</a>.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</strong> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 50,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.<br />
&nbsp;</p>
		
	
		
			
		
	
		
			
		
	
		
			
		
	
